  "prompt": "Is the Tamil language older than Sanskrit? How old is it when compared to all other languages of the world?",
  "response": "The question of whether Tamil is older than Sanskrit is complex and has been the subject of considerable debate among linguists and historians. Both Tamil and Sanskrit are ancient languages with rich histories, but they belong to different language families \u2014 Tamil is part of the Dravidian language family, while Sanskrit is part of the Indo-Aryan branch of the Indo-European family.\n\n**Tamil:**\n- Tamil is one of the oldest surviving classical languages in the world. It has a recorded history that dates back over 2,000 years, with the earliest inscriptions and texts, such as the Tolk\u0101ppiyam, dating back to at least the 1st century BCE. Some archaeological evidence, like the inscriptions found in Adichanallur, suggests that Tamil might have been spoken even earlier, possibly around 500 BCE or earlier.\n\n**Sanskrit:**\n- Sanskrit's earliest form is Vedic Sanskrit, which is the language of the Rigveda, a text dated to approximately 1500 BCE. Classical Sanskrit, as standardized by the grammarian P\u0101\u1e47ini, dates from around the 4th century BCE.\n\nBoth languages have ancient origins, but their historical development occurred in different contexts. While Sanskrit was primarily a liturgical and scholarly language, Tamil has a long history of being both a spoken and written language that has continuously evolved.\n\n**Comparative Age with Other Languages:**\n- In the broader context, languages like Egyptian and Sumerian are older, with written records dating back to around 3000 BCE and older than both Tamil and Sanskrit.\n\nIn summary, both Tamil and Sanskrit are among the oldest languages in the world, but pinpointing which one is definitively older is challenging due to the different types of evidence available for each. Both hold significant places in the historical and cultural development of the Indian subcontinent.",
